Data sources and credits
========================

1. Wiktionary (via Wiktextract / kaikki.org) — PRIMARY source
   Danish word list, meanings, gender, plurals, pronunciation, inflected
   forms, and many example sentences.
   URL: https://kaikki.org/dictionary/Danish/  (JSONL, ~57,800 entries)
   License: CC BY-SA 4.0 (dual-licensed with GFDL by Wikimedia)
   Credit: Wiktionary contributors; Tatu Ylonen / Wiktextract.

2. FreeDict — extra bilingual pairs
   dan-eng 0.3.1 (~5,100 headwords) and eng-dan 0.1.0 (~400 headwords).
   URL: https://freedict.org/
   License: GPL (see the COPYING file inside each FreeDict archive)

3. COR — Det Centrale Ordregister (the Danish Central Word Register)
   Inflected forms (so "husene" finds "hus") and noun gender.
   URL: https://ordregister.dk/ (file cor1.5.1.0.tsv, ~535,000 forms)
   License: CC0 (free for any use)

4. Danish frequency list by hermitdave (from OpenSubtitles 2018)
   Used only to rank words so the most common ones get extra content.
   URL: https://github.com/hermitdave/FrequencyWords
   License: CC BY-SA 4.0

5. AI-generated content
   Example sentences and "gotcha" learner notes for the ~1,000 most common
   words were written by Claude (Anthropic) and are stored in data/ai_cache/.
   They are clearly labeled in the dictionary entries and may contain
   mistakes. They are released under CC BY-SA 4.0 like the rest of the data.
